properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A prolonged period of heavy rain is forecast for the central coast of British Columbia for Thursday and Friday. A pair of frontal waves will make landfall on the central coast of British Columbia on Thursday and Friday. The total rainfall amount from the two sets of frontal waves is forecast to be near 100 mm. The forecast heavy rain on top of antecedent moisture may result in localised flooding or road washouts. Environment and Climate Change Canada meteorologists will continue to refine the forecasts. Rainfall warnings may be issued as the event draws closer. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard conditions with poor visibility in snow and blowing snow are expected or occurring. The first low pressure system that was expected to give blizzard conditions to the community on Tuesday seems to have passed north of the projected track, thus sparing QIkiqtarjuaq from the blizzard conditions predicted today. However a second developing low may move in Wednesday morning, with north to northwest winds strengthening to the 60 gusting 80 km/h range along with snow, blowing snow, and blizzard conditions. The blizzard will continue through Wednesday morning, with conditions starting to improve in the afternoon or early evening. During the worst of the blizzard, visibilities of 400 metres or less are expected in the area. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snowfall with total amounts of about 15 cm is expected. A frontal system moving through southeastern British Columbia continues to bring snow to the region. Snow will become at times heavy on Highway 3 - Paulson Summit to Kootenay Pass tonight before tapering off early tomorrow morning as the system exits the region. ### Rapidly accumulating snow could make travel difficult over some locations. Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Weather in the mountains can change suddenly resulting in hazardous driving conditions. Road conditions are available at www.drivebc.ca. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.
